# Agent organization & dev visibility

Goal: always know **who is working on what**, **which branch**, and **whether it reached main** — especially when brainstorming on phone and continuing at home.

## At session start

1. **Rename this chat immediately** (Agents sidebar → Rename, or ask the agent):
   - Format: `[WIP] <topic> — cursor/<branch>`
   - Example: `[WIP] Alignment depth — cursor/alignment-depth`
2. **Check you are on the right branch** — never continue on a merged branch:
   ```powershell
   git branch --show-current
   .\scripts\agent-status.ps1
   ```
3. If starting new work, branch from latest `main`:
   ```powershell
   git checkout main; git pull
   git checkout -b cursor/<short-kebab-topic>
   ```

## During work (local or cloud)

- **One agent = one topic = one `cursor/*` branch.** Do not pile unrelated changes onto an old branch.
- **Cloud agents** push to `origin/cursor/<topic>`. **Local agents** must push the same branch when done — GitHub is the source of truth, not local files alone.
- If resuming phone brainstorming at home: run `.\scripts\agent-status.ps1` first to see what is WIP vs merged.

## At session end

1. Commit and push: `git push -u origin HEAD`
2. Open a PR if none exists (or tell the user the PR link).
3. **Rename chat** to `[PR #N] <title> — cursor/<branch>`
4. After merge: rename to `[merged] <title> — cursor/<branch>`, then `git checkout main && git pull`

## Chat title status prefixes

| Prefix | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| `[WIP]` | Active work, branch may be unpushed |
| `[PR #N]` | PR open, awaiting review/merge |
| `[merged]` | In main — do not add new work here |
| `[stale]` | Branch behind main with no unique commits — safe to delete |
| `[cloud]` | Optional: work started as a cloud agent |

## When the user asks "where am I?"

Run `.\scripts\agent-status.ps1` and summarize: open PRs, WIP branches (ahead of main, no PR), stale branches (behind main), and merged count.
